'''Vecihi Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n''' ({{IPA-tr|<U+02C8>ved<U+0292><U+02C8>i<U+02D0>hi<U+02D0> <U+02C8>ba<U+0283>a<U+027E><U+026F>n|IPA}}; born 1947) is a Turkish Australian historian and author with a special interest in [[Gallipoli Campaign|Gallipoli]].<ref name=Hurriyet>{{cite web |author=Hurriyet Daily News|title=Anzac Peace Prize awarded to Turk for first time|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/default.aspx?pageid=438&n=anzac-peace-prize-given-to-a-turk-for-the-first-time-2010-07-09|accessdate=2012-03-20}}</ref>  His research has been instrumental in bringing a Turkish perspective to Australian migration and the ill fated [[Anzac|ANZAC]] campaign.  He is a well known and popular speaker on the subject of Gallipoli and has co-authored six books in both English and Turkish, used widely as resource material for schools, media, exhibitions and libraries.  Vecihi Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n has written many articles and conference papers on his research and made guest appearances on television features and radio programs on Gallipoli.

For his outstanding service and individual efforts in uniting cultures, Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n received the Victorian Premier's Award for Excellence in Multicultural Affairs<ref>[http://www.legislation.vic.gov.au/domino/Web_Notes/newmedia.nsf/798c8b072d117a01ca256c8c0019bb01/eda8c2defb67dbceca2570ce000048cf!OpenDocument/ "Victorian Premier's Award for Excellence in Multicultural Affairs"]</ref> in 2005.

In 2010, Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n was recognised by the [[Returned and Services League of Australia|RSL]] as a contributor to understanding and world peace and awarded the ANZAC Peace Prize.<ref>[https://assets.clubsonline.com.au/assets/console/document/documents/ANZACAwards10.pdf "ANZAC Peace Prize"]</ref>  He is the only Australian Turk to be so honoured.

==Early life and career==
Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n was born and raised in Istanbul, Turkey.  After completing his studies, he migrated to Australia in 1973 to pursue a career in Chemical Engineering.

Working in the fields of energy and oil & gas engineering, Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n has lived and worked in Australia, Norway, USA, Brazil, Germany and UK.  After many years in management, in 2002 he created his own consultancy.  His long term association with the Department of Industry saw Monash University award Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n the title of ''Honorary Research Associate'' in 2003.

==Gallipoli historian==
Throughout his adult life, Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n has maintained an interest of and study in the World War I campaign at Gallipoli.  His research has consistently explored both the ANZAC and Turkish viewpoints, detailed in the many publications he has co-authored.  Each year, Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n leads [[Anzac Day]] tours and provides an insightful narrative to Gallipoli visitors.

For a decade, Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n was involved with the [http://www.ae2.org.au/home_page.html AE2- Australian submarine project].  Acting as Turkish advisor to the 25-strong team, he travelled to Turkey to survey the submarine in 2007.  His brainchild AE2 Plaque Project has been implemented in Sydney, Fremantle and at Gallipoli.

Of late, Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n has been working as a Research Fellow with Prof John Hall of [[Deakin University]] Business School, publishing research papers such as:
* Reflections on Anzac Day : from one millennium to the next, 2010<ref>[http://www.deakin.edu.au/dro/view/DU:30031149 "Deakin University Business School"]</ref>
* An empirical analysis of attendance at a commemorative event: Anzac Day at Gallipoli, 2010<ref>[http://www.deakin.edu.au/dro/view/DU:30031083 "Deakin University Business School"]</ref>

He has also recently completed his doctoral studies on matters relating to motives of attendance at the Anzac Day commemorative events at Gallipoli.

==ANZAC Peace Prize==
Announced in April annually, The ANZAC Peace Prize is awarded by the RSL to ''recognise any outstanding effort by an Australian citizen who has promoted the concept of international understanding and who, in so doing, has made a contribution to world peace.''
In 2010, the RSL ANZAC Awards Committee awarded The ANZAC Peace Prize to Vecihi Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n ''in recognition of his sustained and enthusiastic commitment to promote relationships between Australia and other communities around the world, particularly in Turkey, with a significant emphasis on his commitment to Rotary Youth Exchange programs and building understanding of the Gallipoli Campaign.''

==Community work==
Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n<U+2019>s community work spans membership of the [http://www.rotarybrighton.com.au/ Rotary Club of Brighton], where he has held both the posts of Director International and District Chairman of Youth Exchange Committee.  His is a Foundation Member of the Bayside Business Board, serving 2 years as Chairman and 1 year as Deputy Chairman.  Ba<U+015F>ar<U+0131>n has also spent 2 years as Chairman of the Bayside Sister Cities Association and is a 20 year veteran member of the Hampton Sailing Club.

==Awards & Recognition==
* 2010 ANZAC Peace Prize
* 2005 Victorian Premier's Award for Excellence in Multicultural Affairs
* 2003 [[Monash University]] Honorary Research Associate

